Wk20 Excretory functions of the liver, biliary and pancreatic secretions 

Friday, August 25, 2017 

12:36 PM 

List the functions of the liver 

The liver receives portal blood form the stomach, small/large bowels, pancreas and spleen. It biotransforms and degrades substances taken up from the blood and either returns them to circulation or excretes them into bile. It stores carbohydrates, lipids, vitamins, minerals, and synthesises carbohydrates, protein, and intermediary metabolites.  

 

Note that blood supply to the liver involves 75% portal vein, 25% hepatic artery. Outflow is 100% to vena cava.  

 

The liver receives both endogenous (bile salts, bilirubin) and exogenous (drugs, toxins) molecules. The hepatocyte first imports the molecule from blood across basolateral (sinusoidal) membrane. It then transports the molecule within the cell, then chemically modifies/degrades it, then excretes the molecule into bile across the apical (canalicular) membrane. Alternatively, it can return the substance to circulation by secreting it back across the basolateral membrane. Blood from the sinusoids is carried toward the central vein, then back toward IVC. 

 

The liver secretes H2O, HCO3-, bile salts, excretory products. This is stimulated by nerves. Note cholecystokinin expels bile from the gallbladder.

Describe the components of bile 

Bile acids are useful in bile. Other excretions which accompany it in bile include salts such as Na+, K+, Ca2+, Cl-, HCO3-, proteins, cholesterol, bilirubin, fatty acids, phospholipids, steroid hormones, and drugs/drug metabolites.  

 

Describe the waste products commonly excreted in bile 

 

Describe the function of the gallbladder: mechanisms for concentration of bile and the endocrine mechanisms stimulating contraction and secretion of bile into the GIT 

 

The gallbladder allows up to 90% of the water in bile to be absorbed into the bloodstream via epithelial cells, consequently concentrating the bile. The relative tones of the gallbladder and sphincter of Oddi determine whether bile flows from the common hepatic duct into the gallbladder or into the duodenum.  

 

During the non-digestive period, the sphincter of Oddi is contracted and bile flows into the gallbladder. During the digestive period, cholecystokinin and secretin are released. CCK triggers contraction of the gallbladder and relaxation of the Oddi sphincter. Secretin stimulates the hepatic duct cells to release HCO3- into bile.  

 

Describe the enterohepatic circulation of bile salts 

Bile salts are constantly recycled during the processing of a meal, as the total pool of bile salts is insufficient for the fats in a typical meal. Specific transporters in the terminal ileum move bile salts from the GI lumen into the capillaries. Bile salts are then transported to the liver via portal blood. Hepatocytes take up bile salts from the blood, and increase the secretion of bile salts into the bile canaliculi. 95% of bile released into GIT is recycled via enterohepatic circulation, whilst 5% is lost through feces. 

 

Contrast the mechanism of reabsorption of bile acids/salts in the small intestine versus the colon 

Bile acid transporters are not expressed in the duodenum, jejunum or colon. They are highly expressed in the ileum. Hence the reabsorption of bile acids takes place primarily at the terminal ileum. A small amount of unionised bile acids can be reabsorbed through passive diffusion at the colon.  

 

Describe the consequences of impaired reuptake of bile salts by the GIT 

-Insufficient bile to emulsify fat 

-Inability to absorb nutrients from fat 

-Inability to absorb vitamins A, D, E, K 

-Oily feces 

 

List the functions of the pancreas 

The pancreas is primarily made of exocrine tissue (95%), while the remaining 5% are the endocrine Islets of Langerhans.  

 

Exocrine 

The pancreas produces enzymes which are released into a system of ducts, culminating in the main pancreatic duct which then joins the common bile duct to form the ampulla of Vater. Pancreatic juices are released with bile into the duodenum. 

 

Endocrine 

The Islet cells primarily produce either insulin or glucagon. These are secreted directly into the bloodstream.  

 

List the major components secreted by the exocrine pancreas and the principal cell types involved in this secretion 

 

Exocrine acinar cells: produce trypsinogens, proelastase, proprotease, procarboxypeptidase as zymogens. Active enzymes secreted include amylase, lipase, RNase, DNase, co-lipase. These are all digestive proteins. Other secretions include isotonic saline solution, trypsin inhibitor, and other substances. 

 

Exocrine pancreatic duct epithelial cell: produces isotonic NaHCO3.  

 

Islets of Langerhans cells: beta-cells produce insulin, alpha-cells produce glucagon. Both are hormones regulating metabolic function eg amino acid intake by muscles, lipolysis mediator, etc. 

 

Describe the process of digestive enzyme synthesis and packaging and how this process maintains the integrity of the pancreas 

Digestive enzymes secreted into the pancreatic ducts have the potential to digest and cause significant damage to the pancreas. Mechanisms are in place to prevent this.  

-Enzymes are packed into acidic zymogen granules to inhibit activity in the pancreas.  

-Synthesis of enzymes in an inactive precursor form 

-Secretion of trypsin inhibitor prevents trypsin from performing active digestion while in the pancreas 

 

Describe the mechanisms by which chyme from the stomach is neutralised 

Chyme from the stomach is very acidic, with a pH of around 2. When chyme enters the duodenum, cholecystokinin and secretin are released. CCK causes the release of bile from the gallbladder with pH 6-7. Secretin causes release of HCO3- from pancreas (pH 7-8). Note impact of secretin on hepatic duct cells. The combination of alkali secretions and acidic chyme produces a pH of 7-8.5 in the duodenum essential for pancreatic enzymes to function.  

 

Describe the mechanisms by which pancreatic zymogens are activated in the small intestine 

Enteropeptidase enzyme at the brush border activates trypsinogen into trypsin by removing a peptide fragment. Trypsin then cleaves peptide fragments from other zymogens, activating them.  

 

Describe the neural and endocrine regulation of pancreatic exocrine function 

During the cephalic (sight and smell of food) and gastric (volume and composition of food entering stomach) phases, the brain sends efferent signals through the dorsal motor nucleus of the vagus (pre-ganglion). The post-ganglionic neuron releases gastrin-releasing peptide (GRP), causing G cells at the antrum of the stomach to secrete gastrin. Gastrin binds to CCK-A receptors in the acinus, causing release of H2O and enzymes. Alternatively, a different pathway can be used where a post-ganglionic neuron supplies ACH to an M3 receptor, causing H2O and enzyme secretion.  This pathways also supplies ACH to M3 receptors on pancreatic duct cells to cause HCO3- secretion.  

 

During the intestinal phase, the composition of chyme is measured as it enters the small intestine. The products of fat and lipid breakdown stimulate a vagovagal reflex which stimulates the acinar cells. These products also stimulate I cells in the duodenum to secrete CCK, which acts on receptors on acinar cells to stimulate enzyme secretion. H+ stimulates S cells in the duodenum to produce secretin, which acts on receptors on duct cells to stimulate HCO3- release.
